# Communication

When something is complicated, lead with a diagram and concrete details. Don't underestimate what I know — let me ask if I need clarification. Every stone turned, but lean. Plain words. No bloat, no throat-clearing, no metaphors that don't earn their keep.

# What paperflow is

paperflow runs in **one Claude Code instance** — the orchestrator. That single instance creates Goals, designs the task graph, dispatches subagents to do focused work, claims Tasks atomically in Beads while a subagent runs, closes them on verification, and routes browser button clicks back into its own session via the bridge. The orchestrator's job is *context*: knowing the active Goal, the active Phase within it, the currently claimed Task, the dependency graph above and below it, and the ground truth in Beads.

The orchestrator never does long-form work itself — it delegates. `paperflow-plan`, `paperflow-build`, `paperflow-review` all spawn subagents for the actual writing, coding, reviewing. The orchestrator reads the next ready Task within the active phase, claims it in Beads, hands a focused prompt to a subagent with the Task ID and goal+phase context in scope, waits for verified output, then closes the Task. When the active phase empties, the orchestrator advances to the next phase. The bridge is the only inbound channel; subagent fan-out is the only outbound channel; Beads is the only persistent state.

# Goals + Phases + Tasks

The hierarchy is **Goal → Phase → Task**, mapped 1:1 to Beads' native hierarchical IDs (`bd-a1b2.1.1`). Every non-trivial Goal opens with three default phases — **pre-flight**, **build**, **review** — and each phase holds the work-tasks for that stretch.

| Layer | Beads kind | Example ID | Lives at |
|---|---|---|---|
| Goal  | `kind:goal`  | `bd-a1b2`     | top-level Beads task |
| Phase | `kind:phase` | `bd-a1b2.2`   | child of the goal-task |
| Task  | (work-task)  | `bd-a1b2.2.3` | child of the phase-task |

Two pointer files in `<repo>/.paperflow/` track what's active in this checkout:

    <repo>/.paperflow/active-goal     # one line: bd-a1b2
    <repo>/.paperflow/active-phase    # one line: bd-a1b2.2

Lookup walks up from cwd to the nearest `.paperflow/`. When neither file exists anywhere up to `/`, there's no active goal/phase — paperflow falls back to whatever-Goal-is-newest behaviour. Both pointers are written by `paperflow-goal` (on Goal creation) and `paperflow-resume` (on switch).

# The six skills

Six skills, all `paperflow-*` prefixed. The cap is hit exactly — adding a new skill requires removing or merging an existing one. Each one delegates the actual work to a subagent; the skill body is what the orchestrator knows about Goal/Phase/Task context, what subagent prompt it produces, and what Beads mutations bracket the dispatch.

| Skill | One-sentence purpose |
|---|---|
| `paperflow-goal`    | Open / snapshot / archive a Goal — orchestrator creates the goal-task with `kind:goal`, auto-creates three default phase-tasks (pre-flight, build, review), sets the two pointer files, snapshots full state to HTML. |
| `paperflow-plan`    | The signature paperflow move — orchestrator delegates to a subagent that drafts a plan, grills it with 8–15 pointed questions, revises with the user. The result becomes work-tasks linked into the active phase. |
| `paperflow-build`   | Orchestrator claims the next ready task in the active phase, delegates execution to a subagent in that Task's context, verifies on return, closes. Advances the active-phase pointer when the current phase empties. |
| `paperflow-review`  | Orchestrator opens a review-task linked to its parent build-task, delegates the review to a subagent. Closes on approval; reopens the build-task on rejection. Site audits live here too. |
| `paperflow-install` | Bootstrap Beads, install / upgrade paperflow, write a new skill (delegated), write a changelog. The "what is paperflow?" entry point. |
| `paperflow-resume`  | Mirrors Claude Code's `/resume` — list Goals, user picks, the active-goal pointer flips, the active-phase pointer defaults to the first incomplete phase, the Goal HTML opens via the cmux tab-reuse contract. |

# Beads — task layer

paperflow uses Beads (`bd`) as the system of record for goals, phases, and tasks. Goals live as Beads tasks tagged `kind:goal`; phases as `kind:phase` children; work-tasks as children of phases. `paperflow-build` claims tasks via `bd update <id> --claim` and closes via `bd update <id> --close`. `bd ready --label goal-<slug>:phase-<name>` returns the next ready work-task within the active phase.

Install: `brew install beads` or `npm i -g beads`. Per-repo init: `paperflow-bd-init` (run once on first Goal in a repo).

# Specs, plans, design docs

Write them as standalone HTML files in `~/docs/paperflow/{specs,plans,grills}/`, not Markdown. Mermaid via CDN script. Article-style typography (ingress, brødtekst, captioned figures, serif body, sans headings) — never ship inline `<style>` blocks; the typography lives in the shared stylesheet. Each doc links it once from `<head>`:

    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/paperflow/_lib/doc.css">

Use the documented classes — `.eyebrow`, `.byline`, `.ingress`, `<figure>` + `<pre class="mermaid">` + `<figcaption><b>Figure N.</b> …</figcaption>`. Per-doc colour overrides set `:root` CSS variables before the link. Distribute diagrams throughout — each section that explains a flow / comparison / decision gets a Mermaid figure. Aim for at least one visual every ~300 words. Always open via the live-reload URL, never `file://`:

    open http://localhost:8765/paperflow/specs/<filename>.html
    open http://localhost:8765/paperflow/plans/<filename>.html

`__LR_LABEL__` LaunchAgent serves `~/docs/` on port 8765 with WebSocket hot reload (~200 ms refresh).

## Action buttons (every spec & plan)

End every spec / plan / grill HTML with a one-line `<script src="/paperflow/_lib/doc.js"></script>` include. Doc.js auto-injects the right buttons based on the URL path:

| Doc type | Primary | Secondary |
|---|---|---|
| `/specs/*.html`  | Create plan from this spec  | Grill the spec |
| `/plans/*.html`  | Build this plan             | Grill the plan |
| `/grills/*.html` | Submit (handled by `_lib/grill.js`) | — |

Buttons POST to `__BR_LABEL__` (LaunchAgent on `localhost:8766`), which routes the message into the originating terminal tab via AppleScript / tmux / iTerm so I see the prompt land where I'm working.

Before the doc.js include, set:

    <script>
      window.CLAUDE_TARGET = /* paste output of ~/.local/bin/paperflow-target */;
      window.DOC_PATH = "<this-filename>.html";
    </script>

Get the target via:

    ~/.local/bin/paperflow-target

## Live-render

Live-render is **mandatory and on by default** for every paperflow HTML — `doc.js` injects `live-render.{css,js}` on every load. The script itself short-circuits when `location.hostname` isn't in the allowlist (`localhost`, `127.0.0.1`, `::1`), so printed PDFs, emailed copies, and USB exports never try to open a WebSocket they can't reach. To opt out from a specific page (e.g. a fixed-snapshot demo), set:

    <script>window.PAPERFLOW_NO_LIVE_RENDER = true;</script>

…before the `doc.js` include.

## Grills (plan stress-tests)

Grills are the stress-test phase of `paperflow-plan` — generate 8–15 specific questions across categories (architecture, edge cases, failure modes, observability, scope, security, operations, testing, open decisions). Each question must include `rationale`, `recommendation`, `recommendationReason`, and (almost always) a Mermaid `diagram`. Use the shared renderer at `/paperflow/_lib/grill.{css,js}`.

# Statusline

When this repo has an active goal (`<repo>/.paperflow/active-goal` exists), the bottom-bar statusline shows the goal slug, the active phase + position in the phase sequence, and the currently claimed Task with progress through the active phase. No setup needed beyond `paperflow-goal` having created the pointer files. The shape, at full width:

    137,420 / 1M · 1209d022 · onboarding-revamp · ▸ phase 2/3: build · ▸ bd-a1b2.2.3 wire-bridge · 4/9 · main

The statusline composes from a pre-rendered cache at `~/.paperflow/statusline.txt` (written by every Beads-mutating skill on claim/close); when stale, it falls through to live composition via `bd show / bd list --json`. Width-driven truncation drops phase first below 120 cols, then the task subsegments, then branch, project, session-id, in that order.

# Doc review (mandatory)

Every paperflow doc write goes through `paperflow-validate` automatically — a PostToolUse hook fires on Write|Edit of any HTML under `~/docs/paperflow/{specs,plans,grills,notes,changelog,goals,audits}/`, parses every Mermaid block (both `<pre class="mermaid">` and grill-style JS-literal `diagram:` strings), and surfaces failures as a `<system-reminder>` so Claude sees them before reporting the URL. Iterate up to 3 times to fix syntax errors before handing the URL to the user.

# Visual evidence

When a plan touches the UI — HTML, CSS, JSX, TSX, Vue, Svelte, Tailwind, styling, animation, hover, focus, layout, transition, color, spacing, typography, component — capture pre-flight evidence before drafting the plan and embed the resulting `<figure>` blocks in a "Pre-flight evidence" H2 near the top. Pre-flight capture is folded into `paperflow-build`'s entry — it lands naturally in the *pre-flight* phase. After the build, capture the post-flight half and render the proof page at `~/docs/paperflow/changelog/<date>-<topic>-changelog.html` with before/after side-by-side.

- Captures live in `~/docs/paperflow/captures/<date>-<topic-slug>/` (shared across before + after; referenced by the changelog via relative `../captures/.../`).
- Web surfaces use the `visual-investigator` subagent (Chrome DevTools MCP). Native macOS uses OpenClaw + `screencapture -v`.
- One changelog per shipped UI change. The `/changelog/` URL pattern auto-opens via the PostToolUse hook and `doc.js` injects a single Share button.

## Visual capture (visual-investigator)

`visual-investigator` is the unified expert across four backends: Chrome DevTools MCP (single page, default), Unlighthouse (whole-site audits via `~/.local/bin/paperflow-audit-site`), BrowserBase (cloud parallel + cross-browser, future), and OpenClaw + `screencapture` (native macOS). The skill briefs the agent with a structured `{surface, target, captures_needed, …}` JSON; the agent picks the right backend per the matrix in `~/.claude/agents/visual-investigator.md` and returns `{ok, artifacts, notes?}`. Skills stay thin orchestrators — they never name a backend, the agent never re-parses natural language.

For whole-site audits specifically, the `paperflow-review` skill triggers on "audit my site", "lighthouse on X", "SEO check", "show me every page", "site overview". Output lands at `~/docs/paperflow/audits/<date>-<slug>/index.html`. Pre-req (opt-in): `npm install -g @unlighthouse/cli puppeteer`.

# Subagent-driven workflow (the architecture)

paperflow IS subagent-driven — the orchestrator delegates every non-trivial step to a subagent (Task / Agent tool, appropriate `subagent_type`). This is no longer guidance; it's the architecture. The main session is for orchestration, decisions, and synthesis — never for raw tool output, file dumps, or exploration.

| Delegate to subagent | Keep in main session |
|---|---|
| Research (searching, reading many files, web fetches, codebase exploration) | Decisions ("which approach", trade-off calls) |
| Execution (each step of a plan, batched code edits, running tests) | Synthesis (presenting subagent results clearly) |
| Long-form writing (the body of specs/plans/grills/notes) | Conversation with me |
| Tool-heavy work (>500 tokens of raw output) | Quick back-and-forth |

**Why:** A 1M context window degrades past ~50%. Subagents burn their own context on the work and return only the distilled result. The orchestrator always has a perfectly synthesized view on top. More expensive in tokens, much better behavior over long sessions.

**For paperflow:** `paperflow-plan` spawns subagents for draft + grill; `paperflow-build` spawns one per claimed task; `paperflow-review` spawns one per review-task. The orchestrator surfaces the URL + 1–3 sentence summary.

**Default subagent_type:** `general-purpose` for most work. `Explore` for read-only codebase searches. `Plan` for architectural design. Specialized agents when their description fits.

**Brief subagents like a smart colleague:** explain the goal, what's already known, what artifact to produce. Cap response length when relevant.

# OpenClaw delegation

OpenClaw is at /opt/homebrew/bin/openclaw, gateway runs as LaunchAgent. Local LLM agent
with full GUI automation (Peekaboo: click, type, dialogs, screenshots, menus), YOLO exec
policy, embedded inference (~9s/turn). Treat as digital deputy.

When about to ask the human to manually do something on this computer that you cannot do
via your tools or MCP servers, first consider OpenClaw. It can plausibly handle: GUI
dialogs, app forms, Mac apps (Mail, Messages, Calendar, Finder), browser actions outside
Chrome DevTools MCP, shell commands needing the user's environment.

Default aggressiveness on a 1–5 scale is **4** — lean toward auto-execute when criteria
are met.

**Auto-execute tier** — short, scoped, reversible GUI/system tasks. May chain up to 3
discrete sub-actions in a single delegation (e.g. open System Settings → click Privacy →
toggle X). Anything longer falls into suggest-only. File reads inside ~/docs and
~/Downloads stay in auto-execute scope.

Ask "Want me to send this to OpenClaw?" → on yes, run via Bash:

    ~/.local/bin/openclaw-delegate --message "<task>" --json --timeout 60

Default timeout is 60s. Per-task override to 120s allowed when Claude can name a concrete
reason ("remote login", "App Store download"); otherwise 60s.

Parse JSON. For state-changing tasks, ALWAYS run a targeted re-query (regardless of exit
code) to confirm the state actually changed. The re-query result determines success/failure
for the failure-cascade counter, not the openclaw exit code. Do NOT use screenshot/vision
verification — too slow and expensive.

If the wrapper exits non-zero with `{"error":"busy","waited_ms":30000}`, OpenClaw is busy
with another delegation. Tell the user "OpenClaw is busy — want to handle it manually?"
and fall back to asking directly.

**Suggest-only tier** — print the exact command, do not auto-execute. Always
suggest-only, even if short and reversible:

  1. Anything in a browser tab with a logged-in session
  2. Anything that sends a message in Mail / Messages / Slack
  3. Anything in System Settings (privacy, accounts, network)
  4. Anything that signs into a new account
  5. Anything that triggers payment UI

Also suggest-only when the task is multi-app, >3 min, or ambiguous.

**Failure cascade** — keep a session-scoped consecutive-failure counter. Each
auto-execute failure increments it; each success resets it. After 3 consecutive failures,
drop the rest of the session to suggest-only. Counter resets in the next session.

**Gateway down (defensive, currently unused)** — `--local` delegation bypasses the
gateway entirely, so this rule is dormant. If we ever move to gateway-routed delegation:
attempt ONE automatic recovery via `launchctl kickstart -k gui/$(id -u)/ai.openclaw.gateway`,
sleep 1s, retry. If still down, fall back to asking the user.

**Logging** — append every delegation (both tiers) as one line of JSONL to
`~/.openclaw/logs/delegations.jsonl` with shape
`{ts, tier, message, result?, error?, session_id}`.

Skip the offer entirely for physical-world asks, judgment calls, or anything OpenClaw
clearly cannot help with. Chat channels (Telegram, Discord, etc.) are out of scope unless
the user explicitly asks for them.
